Wilkinson's Data Transformations and their Uses:
An Exploration through Real-World Examples

Ryan Lakritz and Melissa Ragonese


In Table 4.1 of Leland Wilkinson's Grammar of Graphics, he defines three classes of variable transforms -- Mathematical, Statistical, and Multivariate. Each class contains a number of data transformations that can be used to clean and normalize data, or discover entirely new trends for analysis. Using these 28 transformations as a template, we have studied various real-world data sets to illuminate a use case of each transformation as it relates to data visualization.

US Econ Census Data

Logarithm Transformation
The mathematical log(x) transformation is easily one of the most popular and widely used data transformations. It is primarily used when dealing with positively (left) skewed data and can be applied to the dependent and/or independent variable(s), depending on the situation. Looking at the 2012 US Economic Census, we find data which is indeed positively skewed.


Mean Function
The mean transformation, mean(x), calculates the average of a vector of values. This is a useful way to compress and summarize many data entries into one meaningful value. In the example below, we used the U.S. Economic Census 2012 data to calculate the mean annual income per person in each state of the U.S. in 2012. This is a number that a viewer of our visualization can relate to.
Below is a plot of mean values:

Sort Transformation
The sort(x) function is used to rearrange the order of a vector of data entries. This helps us to better highlight and visualize trends. In our example, we use the sort function to arrange states in order of average annual income per person and we are able to better understand how the values for each state relate to one another. Rather than having an extremely messy plot that is difficult to read, let alone discover trends, the new sorted graphic allows for comprehensive examination.

Sum Transformation
The sum(x) function is used to add up the entries of a vector and output their total. This is often a useful step in summarizing data or aiding a further transformation. Using data from the U.S. Economic Census in 2002, 2007, and 2012, we calculate the total revenue of each state for each of the three years. The data was originally given as the revenue of each industry in each state; however, this would be unreadable when charted and generally unuseful when attempting to look for trends at the state level.

Rank Transformation
The rank(x) function is used to assign a rank value to each data entry in a vector. This is very helpful for sorting and highlighting the relative relationships between data entries. Using this transformation, we can create a time-series that shows the change in rank of state revenues over a 10 year span.

Group Transformation
The group transformation, grpfun(x1,x2,; f(x)), is when the same function is applied to groups of elements. In this example, we have applied the rank function, as described above, grouped by each year of data. This creates a ranking of the states by revenue for each year in order to finalize the time-series.

Stocks and SAT

In this section, we cover the uses of the Lag, Difference, and Sign data transformations in the creation of a time series of Google stock from April 2014 to April 2015. The time series will color coded to display overall increase and decrease of stock price by month.

We can start with a basic time series to better understand what we are looking at:


ggplot() + geom_line(data = stock, aes(Date, Adj.Close), colour = "navy") + 
    scale_y_continuous(limits = c(475, 600)) + theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), 
    panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "gray"), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), 
    plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5))) + labs(title = "Google Stock Price April 2014 to April 2015", 
    y = "Stock Price")

Next, we endeavor to enhance this detailed time series with information about when the stock is increasing or decreasing overall.

The difference function diff(x1, x2,…, xn), x1-xn vectors is relatively self explanatory. We use it to subtract columns of data from one another.

We use the lag function lag(x), x a vector to shift a time series down a column by one unit, replacing the first entry with 'NA'. This is useful for finding the day to day (or month to month, year to year, etc.) difference between two values. In this case, we use it to shift the column with the stock prices of Google on the last date of each month down an index. We then use the difference function to subtract the lagged column from the original column.

# shift lag column of stock DF down an index and put an NA in the first
# entry.
stock$lag <- c(NA, head(stock["lastdayprice"], dim(stock)[1] - 1)[[1]])

# subtract the lag column from the original price column to find the month
# to month difference
stock$difference <- stock$lastdayprice - stock$lag

# manually calculate the last difference given knowledge of stock value
stock$difference[252] <- 542.56 - stock$lag[252]

# fill in 0s with difference values
temp = 1
for (i in 2:251) {
    if (!(stock$difference[i] == stock$difference[i + 1])) {
        stock$difference[temp:i] <- stock$difference[i + 1]
        temp = i
    }
}

for (i in 2:251) {
    if (stock$difference[i] == 0) {
        stock$difference[i] <- stock$difference[i - 1]
    }
}


We are now capable of plotting the month to month change of Google stock:

ggplot() + geom_line(data = stock, aes(Date, difference), colour = "navy") + 
    theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "gray"), 
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5))) + 
    labs(title = "Google Stock Price Differences April 2014 to April 2015", 
        x = "Difference", y = "Stock Price")

We use the sign function, sign(x), x a vector, to simply determine whether a number is positive, negative, or 0 by mapping it to 1, -1, or 0 respectively. In this case, we look at the sign of the month to month difference in the stock price.

# Assign a 1,-1, or 0 to positive, negative, and 0 numbers respectively in
# the difference column.
stock$sign <- sign(stock$difference)

stock$pos <- stock$Adj.Close
stock$neg <- stock$Adj.Close


We are now capable of plotting the sign of the month to month change of Google stock:

ggplot() + geom_line(data = stock, aes(Date, sign), colour = "navy") + theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), 
    panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "gray"), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), 
    plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5))) + labs(title = "Google Stock Price Differences April 2014 to April 2015", 
    x = "Sign of Price Change", y = "Stock Price")

Here is the final product of our use of the lag, difference, and sign functions:
Where the line is green, Google saw an overall increase in price for that month. Similarly, where the stock is red, Google saw an overall decrease for that month. With a visual like this, we can search for trends in the day to day behavior of a stock during times when it sees an overall increase or decrease.

for (i in 1:252) {
    if (stock$sign[i] < 0) {
        stock$pos[i] <- 0
    } else {
        stock$neg[i] <- 0
    }
}

ggplot() + geom_line(data = stock, aes(Date, pos), colour = "green") + geom_line(data = stock, 
    aes(Date, neg), colour = "red") + scale_y_continuous(limits = c(475, 600)) + 
    theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "gray"), 
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "black"), plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5))) + 
    labs(title = "Google Stock Price", y = "Stock Price")

SAT Score Distribution

In this section, we use use the rank(), prank(), and cut() data transformations to create a visualization of a distribution of SAT scores. We start with a normal distribution of 10000 scores with mean 1500 and standard deviation 330. First, we look at an altered distribution plot:

frequency <- as.data.frame(table(testscores$scores))
colnames(frequency) <- c("scores", "frequency")
merge <- merge(testscores, frequency, by="scores")

ggplot(merge, aes(scores)) + geom_histogram(binwidth=1) + theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "gray"), panel.background = element_rect(fill="white"), plot.title = element_text(size=rel(1.5))) + labs(title="SAT Score Distribution", x="Score", y="Frequency") + scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(400,2400,300))

The prank() Function
The prank() data transformation is a short hand for the word percent rank. In a vector of numerical values, prank() is used to calculate the proportion of data entries that a specific data entry is greater than or equal to. For example, in the list {1,5,6,7}, the entry 6 has a prank of 75% because it is greater than or equal to 3 out of 4 of the lists elements. Since the R programming language does not have a specific prank() function, we calculate prank(scores) by (rank of a score/total scores)*100. We then assign each value in the distribution its percent rank. Below, weve used prank() to color our distribution of SAT Scores.

#use of rank() data transformation
merge$rank <- rank(merge$scores)

#use rank to find percent rank - or prank() data transformation
merge$prank <- 100*(rank(merge$scores)/length(merge$scores))

#use of cut() to create percent range bins
merge$cutprank <- cut(merge$prank, breaks = seq(0, 100, by = 25))

#plot frequency distribution with color by percent rank.
ggplot(merge, aes(scores)) + geom_histogram(binwidth=1, aes(colour=cutprank)) + theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "gray"), panel.background = element_rect(fill="white"), plot.title = element_text(size=rel(1.5))) + labs(title="SAT Score Distribution", x="Score", y="Frequency") + guides(color=guide_legend(title="Percent Rank")) + scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(400,2400,300))

With this information, it is easy to see in which percentile range a specific score falls. Another way we can use prank() to better visualize our SAT data is to just highlight one of the percent ranges by making only the top 25% of score frequencies green and the rest of the plot black.

#plot distribution with only the top 25% green
ggplot(merge, aes(scores)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, aes(colour=cutprank)) + theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "gray"), panel.background = element_rect(fill="white"), plot.title = element_text(size=rel(1.5))) + labs(title="SAT Score Distribution", x="Score", y="Frequency") + guides(color=guide_legend(title="Percent Rank")) + scale_colour_manual(values = c("black","black", "black", "green")) + scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(400,2400,300))

Mortality

In this section, we demonstrate the use of the arcsine, median, mode, cut, quotient, residual, influence, and miss data transformations to explore the World Health Organizations data on mortality by country in 2009 and 2010. By applying each individual transformation or a combination of transformations, we can analyze the data in different ways, pulling new information each time.

Arcsine Data Transformation
The arcsine data transformation is a widely used method of normalizing proportion data (data from 0 to 1) for linear regression. It is calculated as arcsin(sqrt(x)), where x is a vector of values between 0 and 1. Though the arcsine transformation is especially popular in the analysis of proportional data, it is a controversial method, and many have argued that the boxcox power transformation is a better alternative to the arcsine transformation.
We demonstrate the arcsine transformation here in a visualization of the proportion of total deaths that occur in each age range (infant to elderly):

In the histogram and density distributions below, we can see that the post-transformation data has a more linear and normalized trend than the pre-transformation data.

We can evaluate just how effective the arcsine data transformation was by running a robust linear regression on the data. Once the regresssion is fitted, well use the residual and influence transformations to analyze each regression.

Residual Data Transformation
The residual data transformation is used in conjunction with a linear regression on a set of data to calculate how much distance there is between each of the data values and the predicted regression values. While correlation coefficients are widely used to understand a models goodness of fit, residuals provide an effective way to visualize it - the larger the residuals, the farther the actual data points are the model, and thus, the less accurate the model.
With the example of proportions of total deaths that occur in each age range, we ran a linear regression on the data before and after the arcsine transformation. We then calculated and plotted the residuals.

In these charts, we can see that the arcsin transformation did in fact improve the residuals and can be considered a useful tranformation for this data:

Influence Data Transformation
Influence() is a measure of how much impact a particular data point has on the correlation between an independent and dependent variable, i.e.the correlation coefficient (r^2 value) of a regression. It is calculated with the following forumla:

influence = (r^2 without data point) - (r^2 with data point)

The influence of a data point can be helpful in identifying which points in a data set are helpful to the trend found in a specific regression and which points are decreasing its goodness of fit. Here we calculate and visualize the influence of each data point. The size of each data point is proportional to its influence and provdies an easy way to visualize the difference between the non-transformed and arcsin transformed data. It becomes clear that the non-transformed data points have influences in the range of (-.1,.1) while the arcsin tranformation creates the influence range (0,.2), fortifying the utility of this transformation.

In the following visualizations, we can see that in post arcsine transformation, every data point increases the correlation of the regression model, indicating that the model is a relatively better fit than in the pre arcsine transformation, where some of the data points decrease the correlation.

The Miss Data Transformation
The miss() transformation is used to impute missing data. This is to say, where data points are missing from a data set, miss() predicts what those values should be and fills them in. One of the most common ways to implement a miss() transformation is to run a regression and replace all NA values with the value predicted by the regression. The simplest form of this is to use a linear regression; however, there are other models that can help account for randomness in data by taking errors into account (see Gellman Ch 25). All values that were previously present remain unaltered.
Here we run a miss() transformation on the Deaths24 variable, which contains roughly 15000 missing values, in order to reanalyze the proportions of death in each age range. By linearly regressing Deaths24 on Deaths2-Deaths23, we predict the values and impute into the missing data. The r^2 coefficient for this regression is .99, so we can assume that the predicted values should fit well. Once the values of Deaths24 are imputed, we finally recalculate the sum of total deaths to reconfigure the proportions.

As you can see, this alters the shape of the distribution and could cause one to question the validity of ommiting missing data in this case.

Median Data Transformation The median is one of the most commonly used properties of a data set. It describes the value that is positioned exactly in the middle of the set. The median is a valuable piece of data because it allows us to see the exact midpoint of a data set, at which 50% of the data falls below the median and 50% of the data lies above it. One key difference it has from the mean is that it is not effected by outliers.

In this application of the median, we look at the change in world infant mortality rate over time. This allows us to clearly visualize a decreasing trend in infant mortality rate over time, with key improvements coming at the year 2000.

Mode Data Transformation The mode describes the data value that appears the most times in a data set. The mode is often helpful for identifying which value applies to the largest portion of at a data set. With the WHO mortality data, we looked at the death counts by age in each country and identified the age at which most of each countrys deaths occurred. We present the result as a heat map, with the hue representing the most common age-range of death in each country. This allows us to view geographic trends, such as in which countries the most common age of death is high and which are infant deaths. However, the most striking takeaway is the fact that the mode of South African mortality is 30-34.

Quotient Data Transformation
The quotient(x1,x2) data transformation divides elements in a vector x1 by its corresponding elements in another vector, x2. The vectors x1 and x2 must be the same length for the quotient function to be valid. Often, quotient() is used to find the number of items per category, for example, number of trees per square foot or number of computers per household. In the WHO data, we use the quotient function to find the infant mortality rate in each country by calculating:
infant mortality rate = (number of infant deaths)/(total infant population)

Cut Data Transformation
The cut data transformation takes sorted data and cuts it into n ranges of values. This is helpful for taking many values that may be difficult to compare and consolidating them into a small number of ranges that can hold more immediate meaning in a visualization. Here, we use the cut function to color countries in a heat map by which of four ranges of infant mortality rate values their infant mortality rate falls into.
